&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence from the 
[normal]Chartered Institution of Highways and Transportation (CIHT) (SRN 035)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CIHT is a membership organisation representing over 12,000 people who work in the highways and transportation sector.  CIHT members plan, design, build, operate and maintain best-in-class transport systems 
[normal]and infrastructure, whilst respecting the imperatives of improving safety, ensuring economic competitiveness and minimising environmental impact.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CIHT welcomes the opportunity to submit evidence to the Transport
[normal] Select Committee
[normal]’
[normal]s
[normal] consultation on 
[normal]the Stra
[normal]tegic Road network
[normal]. 
[normal]This response incorporates the views of CIHT’s Council which 
[normal]is a 
[normal]represent
[normal]ative body of our members
[normal]’
[normal] interests and opinions
[normal]. We would welcome the opportunity to expand upon our response as required.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CI
[normal]HT welcomes the recognition of 
[normal]the importance of 
[normal]certainty of investment an
[normal]d reform to the Highways Agency set out in Action for Roads. 
[normal]More radical changes to the management of the network may have the capacity for greater improvements in the longer ter
[normal]m 
[normal]and it is encouraging
[normal] that such options have been considered in Action for Roads.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The standard of highway expertise in the 
[normal]United Kingdom
[normal] is very high and is recognised worldwide. Our networks are amongst the safest in the world and our professional stan
[normal]dards are highly regarded. The 
[normal]United Kingdom
[normal] has contributed significantly to the development of highways as an increasingly more efficient sector of industry.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]It is therefore appropriate that Action for Roads proposes an incremental change to the 
[normal]management of the Strategic road network that builds on that expertise. Nevertheless the changes that are required do require 
[normal]a boldness
[normal] in approach so that the investment proposed can be used effectively to deliver real improvements to customers over time
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Certainty
[normal],
[normal] and continuity
[normal] of investment over a sustained period is important if overall improvements to the network are to be delivered effectively and efficiently. This need for certainty applies both to the reformed Highways Ag
[normal]ency and other “client” bodies and the wider supply chain of organisations working in the sector.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Government needs to provide the certainty required by the supply chain side of the sector to invest in resource and capability to deliver the investment envi
[normal]saged. 
[normal]The Roads Investment Strategy needs to be confirmed and be committed to quickly by all parties. 
[normal]This will allow the Highways Agency to develop a robust pipeline of requirements for its supply chain in a form that allows the supply chain to 
[normal]innovate and invest over a period of time.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CIHT 
[normal]argues
[normal] that there is a clear need for a tra
[normal]nsportation strategy that sets a 
[normal]clear framework of requirements over a sustained period fo
[normal]r all elements of our transportation 
[normal]networks. 
[normal] 
[normal]This strategy (or strategies) should include the strategic and local road networks,
[normal] r
[normal]ail, aviation and ports and set
[normal] out how those networks integrate with one another.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The publication of Action for Roads is welcome in that it 
[normal]sets out the importance of t
[normal]he strategic road network and 
[normal]aims to define the needs of the strategic road network, linking investment over a period to the management structure required to deliver it. There is a concern that the absence of a national transport strategy (or strategies) 
[normal]may mean that the investment identified in Action for Roads is not utilised effectively. The strategy should cove
[normal]r
[normal] other transport modes and importantly the overarching policy for the local roads network.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In developing its approach the government needs t
[normal]o ensure that the importance of understanding how customer needs are addressed in the new model for operation and be specific about how those needs are developed, protected and monitored by a regulator or other arrangement.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The government needs to be bold in recognising the capabilities required of a reformed Highways Agency. Those capabilities are likely to include a clearer appreciation of customer requirements and an expanded commercial capability, informed 
[normal]by other sectors. There is also a need for the reformed organisation to have more freedom to allow more innovation and more agility in decision making.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Government should recognise that the success of an improved 
[normal]strategic network in meeting customer needs cannot be met without the local road network being also considered as part of a holistic solution that customers require.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Department for Transport and government need to clearly define the role of the transp
[normal]ortation network in delivering the policies of the government. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Action for Roads envisages the publication of a draft national policy statement on national networks in 2013. This needs to clearly set out the relationship of the strategic network to other 
[normal]networks, including the local highway network. It also needs to demonstrate how the policy links to both national and local planning policy, setting out a clear framework for the responsibility and accountability of developing the network.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The 
[normal]response to
[normal] the questions are
[normal] set out on the following pages.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]1.1.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]CIHT welcomes the recognition of 
[normal]the importance of 
[normal]certainty of investment and reform to the Highways Agency.  
[normal]1.2.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The current proposals to be enacted in legislation within this Parliamentary cycle offer a pragmatic and deliverable approach to change.  More 
[normal]radical changes
[normal], for example the introduction of a Regulated Utility Model in conjunction with direct user charging,
[normal] to the management of the network may have the capacity for greater improvements in the longer term and it is good that such options have be
[normal]en considered in Action for Roads.
[normal]1.3.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Certainty of investment over a sustained period is important if overall improvements to the network are to be delivered effectively and efficiently. This need for certainty applies both to the reformed Highways Agency and
[normal] other “client” bodies and the wider supply chain of organisations working in the sector. 
[normal]1.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The five year funding period set out (in the Road Investment Strategy) is a welcome improvement from annualised budget cycles.  However, this falls short of the peri
[normal]ods required to undertake a holistic approach to asset management and delivery of customer expectations.  
[normal]1.5.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Experience from other models and schemes, for example on the M25 D
[normal]esign Build Finance &amp; Operate
[normal] scheme, and PFI investments in the local highway sect
[normal]or have delivered real benefits through considering needs over a 25 year period.  Such approaches have enabled ambitious investment programmes to be delivered over a five year period followed by managed, longer operational periods. This 'invest to save' ap
[normal]proach helps reduce ongoing operational costs through upfront investment in the asset. 
[normal]1.6.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Certainty of investment over a sustained period will also allow a more resilient network to be developed, allowing the reformed Highways Agency and its supply chain to 
[normal]meet the potential challenges of climate change by taking a longer term view of the needs of the network.
[normal] 
[normal]1.7.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The increased level of investment is also welcomed as the sector has faced budget reductions that have led to asset deterioration.
[normal] The investment ide
[normal]ntified will enable a series of key benefits to be delivered such as improving capacity, reducing congestion and improving reliability. These benefits will improve the network for users and deliver environmental benefits
[normal]..
[normal]1.8.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The sector already has a lot of e
[normal]xperience to build on.  For instance, the lessons learnt from the managed motorways programme already underway have demonstrated the ability of the sector to deliver additional capacity withi
[normal]n existing highway corridors. These improvements have been delive
[normal]red more efficiently than full motorway improvements, delivering benefits to users and the environment in a shorter timescale.
[normal]1.9.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Future Investment strategies should be informed by linking an understanding of the assets required to deliver all the purposes of
[normal] the network derived from customer need. A proposed approach is set out in our response to Question 3 below.
[normal]1.10.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Certainty of investment and clarity of the pipeline of works anticipated is fundamental to the ability of the supply chain to deliver a significant
[normal] programme of investment in the timescales set out. If certainty is not delivered then 
[normal]providing 
[normal]increased resource will have a time lag before benefits can be 
[normal]fully 
[normal]delivered.
[normal]1.11.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It is welcome that the importance of the local road network is recognised by Ac
[normal]tion for Roads and that the effects on non-vehicular highway users are addressed to some degree. 
[normal]1.12.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Nearly all journeys on the strategic road network begin and end on the local highway network. Unless linked to consideration of wider effects, improvements to
[normal] the strategic road network (SRN) may have significant effects upon the local road network affecting all highway users, local communities and the environment. These effects may occur through diversion onto unsuitable parts of the network by charging, conge
[normal]stion or control of access to the SRN. Customers do not take a different view of the networks they travel 
[normal]on,
[normal] a consistent appropriate standard of service delivery needs to be the aim.
[normal]1.13.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The issue of how the viewpoint of customers is taken into account in th
[normal]e development of the network is fundamental to real and lasting improvements in the network. The role of a “regulator” acting in customers interests is commonplace in other sectors and in the transport sector and should be introduced alongside changes to t
[normal]he form of the Highways Agency in the way it manages the network. We set out in our response to Question 3 below how the requirements of customers should be 
[normal]developed,
[normal] a regulator could play an important role in that.
[normal]1.14.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Consideration of the local road networ
[normal]k in conjunction with highway authorities, Local Transport Boards (LTBs) and Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) is vital and needs to be recognised and implemented as part of the changes proposed set out in Action for Roads.
[normal]1.15.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The increased amount of maint
[normal]enance investment for the local road network is welcome.  However, this must be considered alongside a reduced revenue budget for local authorities. There is the risk that the overall increase in investment could be jeopardised if the issue of the
[normal] 
[normal]contribu
[normal]tion
[normal] that the local network makes to the success of the S
[normal]RN
[normal] is not fully considered.
[normal]1.16.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]CIHT welcomes and supports the importance of the Highways Maintenance Efficiency Programme (HMEP) 
[normal]http://www.dft.gov.uk/hmep
[normal] in delivering change to the local roads sector
[normal] and will continue to work with the programme to ensure that linkages to the development of the SRN are maintained and enhanced.
[normal]&#xa0;
