[normal]2.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]There could be benefit in considering the reform of how improvements to the local road network are delivered. The current arrangement contains inefficiencies, introduces inconsistencies and does not make best use of the pool of ski
[normal]lled resource available.
[normal]2.5.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]How the national and local highway network contributes to and enables planning policy to be developed effectively and sustainably across the country is a clear requirement of government at all levels
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]2.6.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]A clear understanding of the 
[normal]purposes of the highway network for all its customers will help develop that strategy and its development will also allow clear accountability for delivery of the strategy to be set out to the different bodies required to deliver it.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.1.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The contribution that the 
[normal]highway
[normal] netw
[normal]ork is required to make to a range of policy areas should 
[normal]be clearly defined in
[normal] the strategy described above
[normal] in our response to Question 2
[normal]. In order to develop a robust prediction to underpin development of the network a series of 
[normal]key steps should be undertaken a
[normal]longside existing economic modelling tools
[normal]. 
[normal]3.2.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The development of these st
[normal]eps should be undertaken by all engaged in the sector including
[normal] the gove
[normal]rnment, 
[normal]Highways Agency and related authorities on the adjoining networks
[normal], groups representing the sector and the supply chain to the sector. 
[normal]3.3.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The steps CIHT propose, based on a system
[normal]s thinking approach, are:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.3.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Identify the different classes of groups
[normal] (customers)
[normal] who are reliant on the network. As well as 
[normal]different 
[normal]users of the network these customer groups could in
[normal]clude amongst others, adjacent communities, non-
[normal]users of the network, th
[normal]e environment, her
[normal]itage and the highway asset itself.
[normal]3.3.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Identify 
[normal]the different purposes that the network is required to deli
[normal]ver to different customer groups
[normal]3.3.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Analysis to confirm how the network will best meet the different purposes identified and to identify 
[normal]what investment is required to meet those different purposes of all customers.
[normal]3.3.4.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Confirm the wider benefits that will arise from meeting the needs of all customer groups and thereby define the Value for Money of the investment.
[normal]3.3.5.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Identify 
[normal]areas where investmen
[normal]t in other modes will better meet
[normal] the needs of customers and identify the parties best able to deliver that investment
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The investment identified
[normal] should b
[normal]e
[normal] considered alongside the wider econ
[normal]omic
[normal] need
[normal]s
[normal] of the surrounding area. Action for 
[normal]R
[normal]oads proposes 
[normal]route based studies as the basis for d
[normal]eveloping investment strategies. In order to be effective,
[normal] these strategies need to work closely with LE
[normal]P
[normal]s, 
[normal]LTB
[normal]s and local authorities to ensure all appropriate customer needs are addressed.
[normal]3.5.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]I
[normal]n proposing the additional
[normal] analysis outlined above it should be recognised that the strategic road network is required to d
[normal]eliver in such a complex environment
[normal] there can never be a complete answer
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]I
[normal]t is important that benefits are delivered effectively
[normal] against a pipeline with a hi
[normal]gh degree of certainty
[normal] rather than constant refinement of modelling that will never
[normal] be able to
[normal] present a complete
[normal] or accurate
[normal] picture. 
[normal]3.6.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]CIHT suggest that the work proposed above should be carried out alongside existing appraisal of schemes in the short ter
[normal]m.
[normal]3.7.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The role of the regulator identified in the response to question 1 in identifying the needs of customers is an important one t
[normal]o be developed as the Highways Agency changes form.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Significant improvements to the reliability
[normal], 
[normal]efficiency
[normal] and safety
[normal] of travel have already been m
[normal]a
[normal]de on the S
[normal]RN 
[normal]by in
[normal]vestment utilising technology. T
[normal]he increasing 
[normal]length of the network utilising Manage
[normal]d 
[normal]M
[normal]otorway techniques to 
[normal]increase capacity are welcome. T
[normal]he technology available to vehicle users, both in terms of safety and i
[normal]nformation have developed and wi
[normal]ll continue t
[normal]o
[normal] develop rapidly.
[normal]4.2.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The reformed operator of the network needs to work closely with 
[normal]the vehicle development sector to maximise the benefit of investm
[normal]ents both to vehicles and the network. Having c
[normal]larity 
[normal]of customer needs and purposes as outlined in the response to the earlier question
[normal] will play an important role in that development.
[normal]4.3.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Infor
[normal]mation n
[normal]eeds 
[normal]o
[normal]f customers across the whole 
[normal]transport network, including rail should
[normal] be continuously developed from a customer’s perspective. There have been welcome improvements in the information available to customers for end to end journeys which includ
[normal]e walking and cycl
[normal]ing. This information needs to i
[normal]nform the development of the network
[normal] and will
[normal] r
[normal]equire very different
[normal] skills
[normal], based around understanding of customer analysis and needs
[normal] to be bought into the reformed Highways 
[normal]A
[normal]gency from different sectors.
[normal] 
[normal]4.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The way in which technology changes customer behaviour over time will need to be monitored by the reformed Highways Agency and incorporated into the investment planning of the network.
[normal]4.5.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Providers on the network should be given the freedom to utilise techno
[normal]logy in how they deliver services to customers of the network rather than a prescriptive specification of how they provide a service. Continuing improvements in the safety of road workers, 
[normal]bought
[normal] about by the use of technology should be encouraged.
[normal]4.6.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The use
[normal] of technology to regulate access to the network in order to manage traffic volumes
[normal] and release extra capacity
[normal] will be a key area for 
[normal]development, but will require a
[normal] holistic approach with adjoining highway authorities to deliver an effective solution.
[normal]4.7.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The
[normal] use of BIM technology on the highways network should be a focus for the reformed Highways Agency and its supply chain. The use of technology to develop better understanding of whole asset information will lead to more efficient management of the service.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The amount of income derived from Vehicle Excise Duty and fuel du
[normal]ty is significantly more than that spent on the roads network. Parts of the network, particularly the local roads network have significant requirements for investment to maintain the standard of the asset and this has been partially recognised in the addit
[normal]ional expenditure proposed in Action for Roads.
[normal]5.2.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Experience from around the wor
[normal]ld suggests that there is no
[normal] single model that provides an appropriate model for a reformed strategic network to follow
[normal] in terms of increasing investment
[normal]. In many countries the u
[normal]se of tolling to provide an income stream to finance investment has been successful. Clearly introduction
[normal] of a widespread n
[normal]ational road user charging scheme is not envisaged in Action for 
[normal]R
[normal]oads
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]It 
[normal]should not be ruled out 
[normal]however, 
[normal]until a clearer picture o
[normal]f the ultimate investment need of the network, informed by analysis of customer needs has 
[normal]b
[normal]een made. 
[normal]5.3.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is also s
[normal]ensible not to focus on the
[normal] argument between public or private investment. Each is likely to play a role in funding inv
[normal]estment in the future n
[normal]etwork, and more 
[normal]opportunities should be found for Public Private Partnerships in which the Government invests and takes on a minority shareholding. 
[normal]5.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]here have been valuable lessons learnt in the highways sector through the use of Private Finance funded s
[normal]chemes on both the strategic and local networks. Benefits have included:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.4.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A whole life view of service delivery over a significant period of time, with investment occurring over a short initial period follow
[normal]ed by a long period of service delivery t
[normal]o defined performance 
[normal]standards that reflect the needs
[normal] of service users.
[normal]5.4.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Private sector providers, given the certainty of a clear programme of service delivery
[normal] have invested in the development of new techniques and products, leading to efficiency improveme
[normal]nts in service delivery.
[normal]5.4.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A focus on managing long term asset management techniques as risks of performance have been moved to the service provider
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.5.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]hese benefits, combined with a clear consideration of customer needs
[normal] outlined above
[normal] 
[normal]are consistent with man
[normal]y of the features of 
[normal]a regulated asset base
[normal] model used in other sectors. This model may 
[normal]provide the basis for a more robust funding model for the sector. Such a model could incorporate both public and private investment, dependant on different needs of the
[normal] network an
[normal]d
[normal] could incorporate user charging at a future date.
[normal]5.6.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The experience of other sectors, particularly in the rail sector will be useful in this regard. There would be a particular need for clear regulation to consider the needs for investment in the
[normal] asset base.
[normal]5.7.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The move towards a regulated asset base may well present the opportunity for innovative and new funding streams as the supply chain is broadened by entrants from a wider base of sectors. For example the local highway network in particular cont
[normal]ains significant amounts of other regulated assets, such as water, telecoms and power networks, all of which require continued investment. The 
[normal]scope for efficiencies seem
[normal] potentially high. 
[normal]5.8.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The role for specific investment by business to improve networks t
[normal]hat facilitate economic development is one that is already used in the sector but the development of LEPs and LTB’s would point to a wider consideration of the benefits of an enhanced approach.
[normal]5.9.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]A reformed Highways Agency should be less constrained, more ag
[normal]ile and be able to take quicker decisions to attract and encourage more investors.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.1.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]The standard of highway expertise in the United Kingdom is very high and is recognised worldwide. Our networks are amongst the safest in the world and our professional standards are highly regarded. The United Kingdom
[normal] has contributed significantly to the development of highw
[normal]ays as an increasingly more effi
[normal]cient industry.
[normal]6.2.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]It is therefore appropriate that Action for Roads proposes an incremental change to the management of the Strategic road network that builds on that expertise. Nevertheless the changes that are required do require 
[normal]a boldness
[normal] in approach in order that the i
[normal]nvestment proposed can be used effectively to deliver real 
[normal]improvements to the network over time. It would be a mistake to view an incremental change as only a small one requiring minimal investment. 
[normal]6.3.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]All of the groups need to encourage the entry of, and d
[normal]evelopment of young people into the sector to provide the resource required to deliver future investment.
[normal]6.4.[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Our views on the cha
[normal]nges required are set out below:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government[bold]:
[normal]6.4.1.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Department for Transport and government need to clearly define the role of the t
[normal]ransportation network in delivering the policies of the government. Action for Roads envisages the publication of a draft national policy statement on national networks in 2013. This needs to clearly set out the relationship of the strategic network to oth
[normal]er networks, including the local highway network. It also needs to demonstrate how the policy links to both national and local planning policy, setting out a clear framework for the responsibility and accountability of developing the network. It should cle
[normal]arly define the role of government in relation to the reformed Highways Agency.
[normal]6.4.1.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The government needs to be bold in recognising the capabilities required of a reformed Highways Agency. In particular it needs to ensure that the importance of understanding how customer needs should be addressed in the new model for operation and be speci
[normal]fic about how those needs are protected and monitored by a regulator or other arrangement. Those capabilities are likely to include a clear appreciation of customer requirements, understanding of wider stakeholder needs and an expanded commercial capabilit
[normal]y from other sectors. 
[normal]6.4.1.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]There is a need to maintain strong leadership through the process of change whilst the new requirements for the reformed Highways Agency are being fully defined and sourced, using the freedom of the new organisation to bring in new s
[normal]kills and capabilities. This will ensure that momentum on delivering the pipeline of investment set out in Action for Roads is maintained.
[normal]6.4.1.4.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government needs to provide the certainty required by the supply chain side of the sector to invest in resource and c
[normal]apability to deliver the investment envisaged. The Roads Investment Strategy needs to be confirmed and be committed to quickly by all parties so that the Highways Agency can develop a robust pipeline of requirements for its supply chain.
[normal]6.4.1.5.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Government should 
[normal]recognise that the success of an improved strategic network in meeting customer needs cannot be met without the local road network being also considered as part of the solution that customers require.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]A reformed Highways Agency[bold]:
[normal]6.4.2.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Highways Agency needs 
[normal]the capacity and capability to change
[normal], 
[normal]building on the expertise that it has built up and maintaining strong leadership. This must not be lost. 
[normal]6.4.2.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Needs to develop an understanding of the wide range of purposes that the network has and further develop its cu
[normal]stomer relationship capabilities, bringing in capability from other sectors as required. It should build links across sectors to do so.
[normal]6.4.2.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Needs to recognise the importance of linking to authorities with responsibility for the local road network and economic 
[normal]growth including LEPs and LTBs
[normal]6.4.2.4.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Should develop its relationship with the supply chain to give it the freedom to deliver the investment it manages – it should concentrate on ensuring that the investment is focussed in the areas that best meet its 
[normal]customer’s 
[normal]needs.
[normal] 
[normal]Whilst the reformed Highways Agency will still be subject to European Procurement Regulations other unnecessary procedures should be removed.
[normal]6.4.2.5.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Needs to provide information on the pipeline of requirements set out in Action for Roads to its supply chai
[normal]n as soon as possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]6.4.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Supply Chain[bold]:[bold]6.4.3.1.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The supply chain needs to recognise the opportunity offered by Action for Roads and start to invest in the resource and capability required to deliver a significant amount of investment.
[normal]6.4.3.2.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It needs to support the reforme
[normal]d Highways Agency and government in developing an improved sector, bringing expertise from across the world to deliver the investment provided.
[normal]6.4.3.3.[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It needs to recognise the importance of focussing on customers on the network and bring its expertise of deliver
[normal]ing services across both the strategic and local highway networks to help the Highways Agency change its role.
